"Held I.M., Winton M., Takahashi K., Delworth T., Zeng F., Vallis G.K.","Probing the fast and slow components of global warming by returning abruptly to preindustrial forcing",2010,"Journal of Climate","23","9",,"2418","2427",,,10.1175/2009JCLI3466.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77953690318&partnerID=40&md5=f425377f9d87f265959ff5ee11bdff94","NOAA/Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Laboratory, Princeton, NJ, United States; Instituto Geofisico del Peru, Lima, Peru; Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences Program, Princeton University, Princeton, NJ, United States","Held, I.M., NOAA/Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Laboratory, Princeton, NJ, United States; Winton, M., NOAA/Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Laboratory, Princeton, NJ, United States; Takahashi, K., Instituto Geofisico del Peru, Lima, Peru; Delworth, T., NOAA/Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Laboratory, Princeton, NJ, United States; Zeng, F., NOAA/Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Laboratory, Princeton, NJ, United States; Vallis, G.K., Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences Program, Princeton University, Princeton, NJ, United States","The fast and slow components of global warming in a comprehensive climate model are isolated by examining the response to an instantaneous return to preindustrial forcing. The response is characterized by an initial fast exponential decay with an e-folding time smaller than 5 yr, leaving behind a remnant that evolves more slowly. The slow component is estimated to be small at present, as measured by the global mean near-surface air temperature, and, in the model examined, grows to 0.4°C by 2100 in the A1B scenario from the Special Report on Emissions Scenarios (SRES), and then to 1.4°C by 2300 if one holds radiative forcing fixed after 2100. The dominance of the fast component at present is supported by examining the response to an instantaneous doubling of CO2 and by the excellent fit to the model's ensemble mean twentieth-century evolution with a simple one-box model with no long times scales. © 2010 American Meteorological Society.",,"Box models; Climate model; E-folding; Exponential decays; Near surface air temperature; Pre-industrial; Radiative forcings; Slow component; Special report on emissions scenarios; Global warming; Climate models; air temperature; climate change; climate modeling; ensemble forecasting; estimation method; global warming; radiative forcing; twentieth century",,,,,,"Allen, M.R., Stott, P.A., Mitchell, J.F.M., Schnur, P., Delworth, T., Quantifying the uncertainty in forecasts of anthropogenic climate change (2000) Nature, 407, pp. 617-620; Cai, W., Whetton, P.H., A time-varying greenhouse warming pattern and the tropical-extratropical circulation linkage in the Pacific Ocean (2001) J. Climate, 14, pp. 3337-3355; Clement, A.C., Seager, R., Cane, M.A., Zebiak, S.E., An ocean dynamical thermostat (1996) J. Climate, 9, pp. 2190-2196; Delworth, T., GFDL's CM2 global coupled climate models. Part I: Formulation and simulation characteristics (2006) J. Climate, 19, pp. 643-674; Gregory, J.M., Vertical heat transports in the ocean and their effect on time-dependent climate change (2000) Climate Dyn, 16, pp. 501-515; Gregory, J.M., Forster, P.M., Transient climate response estimated from radiative forcing and observed temperature change (2008) J. Geophys. Res., 113, pp. D23105. , doi:10.1029/2008JD010405; Gregory, J.M., Webb, M.J., Tropospheric adjustment induces a cloud component in CO2 forcing (2008) J. Climate, 21, pp. 58-71; Hansen, J.E., Efficacy of climate forcings (2005) J. Geophys. Res., 110, pp. D18104. , doi:10.1029/2005JD005776; Hasselmann, K., Sausen, R., Maier-Reimer, E., Voss, R., On the cold start problem in transient simulations with coupled atmosphere-ocean models (1993) Climate Dyn, 9, pp. 53-61; Kettleborough, J.A., Booth, B.B.B., Stott, P.A., Allen, M.R., Estimates of uncertainty in predictions of global mean surface temperature (2007) J. Climate, 20, pp. 843-855; Knutti, R., Krahenmann, S., Frame, D.J., Allen, M.R., Commen